\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec3 Introduction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 In the era of increasingly complex and dynamic markets, traditional portfolio rebalancing approaches\'97such as fixed\uc0\u8209 interval or static\u8209 threshold models\'97can fall short of capturing rapid regime shifts, sentiment\u8209 driven volatility, and nonlinear cost structures.\
By harnessing artificial intelligence (AI) and advanced statistical techniques, portfolio managers can design more adaptive, cost\uc0\u8209 efficient, and robust rebalancing frameworks.\
This article presents a comprehensive survey of AI\uc0\u8209 powered portfolio rebalancing, organized into three core domains: trigger mechanisms, optimization methodologies, and constraints & cost management.\
We explore how machine learning (ML) and large language models (LLMs) can enhance dynamic drift detection, regime\uc0\u8209 sensitive timing, predictive cost minimization, and tax\u8209 efficient decision\u8209 making.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec3 1. Trigger Mechanisms\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Trigger mechanisms determine 
\f2\i when
\f0\i0  a portfolio should be rebalanced. Rather than relying on fixed calendars or arbitrary drift limits, AI\uc0\u8209 driven triggers adapt to market conditions by detecting regime shifts, measuring dynamic drift, and even parsing unstructured data for sentiment signals.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 1.1 Threshold Models with Dynamic Drift Limits\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Traditional threshold models rebalance when an asset\'92s weight deviates beyond a fixed band (e.g., \'b15%) from its target. AI enhancements instead estimate 
\f2\i dynamic
\f0\i0  drift based on recent volatility regimes:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Random Forest Drift Estimation
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 A random forest regressor learns to predict expected drift magnitude from features such as realized volatility, trading volume, and bid\u8209 ask spreads. By feeding the model a rolling window of these variables, it outputs a time\u8209 varying drift tolerance: larger in low\u8209 volatility regimes and tighter during high turbulence.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Adaptive Bands
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 Using the random forest\'92s output, bands can be set as a multiple of the predicted drift (e.g., \'b11.5\'d7). Portfolios avoid unnecessary churn during quiet periods yet respond swiftly to emerging trends, reducing both performance drag and transaction costs.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 1.2 Regime\uc0\u8209 Aware Rebalancing Frequency\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Markets often follow latent regimes\'97trending, mean\uc0\u8209 reverting, or crisis states\'97that require different rebalancing cadences. Hidden Markov models (HMMs) provide a probabilistic framework for regime detection:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 HMM Training
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 Historical returns, volatility, and macroeconomic indicators feed into an HMM, which learns state transition probabilities and regime\u8209 specific emission distributions. Typical regimes include \'93Bull Trend,\'94 \'93Sideways,\'94 and \'93Bear Volatility.\'94\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Frequency Adjustment
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 Once the current regime is inferred (e.g., >80% posterior probability of a \'93Bear Volatility\'94 state), the rebalance schedule updates accordingly: daily or intraday in high\u8209 vol regimes, weekly or monthly in trending or calm markets. This regime\u8209 aware cadence helps capture drift when it matters most and reduces unnecessary adjustments otherwise.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 1.3 News & Sentiment Triggers via LLM Classification\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Unstructured data\'97news articles, social media, and earnings\uc0\u8209 call transcripts\'97encode forward\u8209 looking signals often overlooked by quantitative\u8209 only frameworks. Large language models (LLMs) can ingest and classify sentiment events:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Sentiment Fine\uc0\u8209 Tuning
\f0\b0 \uc0\u8232 A transformer\u8209 based LLM (e.g., fine\u8209 tuned BERT or GPT variant) is trained on labeled financial news for sentiment polarity (positive, neutral, negative) and event types (e.g., downgrades, M&A rumors).\
\ls3\ilvl0
